---
import DocsLayout from '../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import { Code } from 'astro:components';

const codeRunLocally = `cd docs
npm install
npm run dev`;

const codeValidation = `npm run build`;

const sections = [
  { label: 'Run Locally', href: '#run-locally' },
  { label: 'Authoring Shape', href: '#authoring-shape' },
  { label: 'First Content Pass', href: '#first-content-pass' },
  { label: 'Validation', href: '#validation' }
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Getting Started | sf-bedrock docs"
  description="Getting started with the sf-bedrock Astro documentation site."
  eyebrow="Getting Started"
  sections={sections}
>
  <Fragment slot="header">
    <h1>Open the docs workspace.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      The docs app is intentionally small: an Astro shell, a documentation layout,
      and starter pages that can grow one reliable Bedrock API at a time.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <section class="doc-section" id="run-locally">
    <h2>Run Locally</h2>
    <p>
      The documentation site lives in <code>docs/</code>. Install dependencies in
      that folder, then start the Astro preview server.
    </p>
    <Code code={codeRunLocally} lang="bash" />
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="authoring-shape">
    <h2>Authoring Shape</h2>
    <p>
      Each page should read like a contract: what the tool owns, how production
      code calls it, how tests replace or assert it, and which edge behavior
      developers need to remember.
    </p>
    <div class="doc-grid">
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Contract</h3>
        <p>Name the responsibility before listing methods or examples.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Usage</h3>
        <p>Show the smallest Apex snippet that proves how the API is meant to feel.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Testing</h3>
        <p>Document the mock path and the assertion shape alongside the production path.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Boundaries</h3>
        <p>Separate implemented behavior from roadmap notes and planned names.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="first-content-pass">
    <h2>First Content Pass</h2>
    <p>
      Start with the tools that already exist in <code>force-app/bedrock/lib</code>.
      A useful order is the testing foundation first, then trigger coordination,
      then roadmap pages once the public shape is clearer.
    </p>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong>1. TestData</strong>
        <span>Fast setup examples, mock Ids, relationship fields, and typed casting.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>2. DML</strong>
        <span>Production facade, mock recording, and assertions for operation intent.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>3. Query</strong>
        <span>Single and multiple mock responses, query ordering, and failure expectations.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>4. RecordBuffer</strong>
        <span>Trigger-context staging, grouped flush behavior, and recursion-minded usage.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="validation">
    <h2>Validation</h2>
    <p>
      Build the docs before shipping layout changes. The build is fast and catches
      invalid Astro markup, broken imports, and accidental client-only assumptions.
    </p>
    <Code code={codeValidation} lang="bash" />
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Keep docs trustworthy</strong>
      <p>
        When a page describes Apex behavior, verify it against the current class
        before presenting it as an implemented contract.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
